# **5. ****Known Issues ****&**** Carried Technical Debt**

These are tracked, not hidden. None currently blocks demo scheduling; each has an owner-decided disposition.

| **Item** | **Impact** | **Disposition** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Corporate ↔ Distribution seller identity is unresolved (ADR-0003, “Proposed”) | Corporate Travel cannot complete a real booking end-to-end (this is the Demo Readiness “cut” scene) | Scoped as Workstream 3’s first task — ratify the ADR, then implement |
| Payments refund: a PSP business rejection (e.g. an id Razorpay doesn’t recognise) could surface as a raw 500 | A real cancel-after-real-payment could fail ungracefully | Fixed in PR #96 (routes to a clean REFUND_FAILED state); awaiting final live verification |
| Distribution: an unknown seller ID returns HTTP 500 rather than a clean 4xx | Minor — poor error ergonomics only | Bundle with the ADR-0003 fix in Workstream 3 |
| BFF returns 500 (not 401) on missing/invalid auth | Minor — error ergonomics only | Backlog, not urgent |
| CDP ranking call has a tight (~400ms) cold-start timeout | First personalised search after a cold start can silently fall back to unranked | Mitigated: the demo seed script performs a warm-up call. Revisit the timeout value later. |
| Five thin-slice services log plain text instead of structured JSON | Cosmetic — harder to grep in aggregate log tooling | Backlog, cosmetic |
| A specific CI integration-test flake (cold-container race in Testcontainers) has recurred 3 times, each individually guarded | None currently — all known instances are guarded | If a 4th instance appears, stop guarding one-by-one and split/serialise the heavy CI job instead |
| Local real-payment testing needs an ngrok tunnel and a correctly-scoped Razorpay Dashboard webhook (specific event types, no duplicate webhook entries) | Easy to misconfigure; a missing tunnel makes checkout hang silently with no error | Documented as a standing pre-demo checklist item — see §7.4 |

# **6. ****Roadmap**

## **6.1  Immediate — finishing the Demo Product program**

This is the team’s first work. In order:

- Click through and merge PR #95 (Workstream 2) and PR #96 (payments refund fix).

- Ratify ADR-0003 (corporate↔distribution seller identity), then build Workstream 3 — the Trade portal and the identity fix. This re-enables the Corporate Travel scene cut during Demo Readiness.

- Build Workstream 4 (WhatsApp mock + loyalty member portal) and Workstream 5 (full DCS airport workstation).

- Rewrite the demo script for the finished product (“v3”), then run DR5 — a full click-through dry-run of every persona portal on the real demo stack, including a real Razorpay payment.

- A green DR5 is the gate: at that point the platform is formally schedulable for the client demonstration.

## **6.2  After the demo — Phase 3: Delivery ****&**** Operations**

This is the next major phase of the *original platform roadmap* (independent of the Demo Product program above). Phase 2 deliberately deferred the operationally hardest, safety-adjacent work until the commercial core was proven:

- **DCS depth** — the thin check-in→boarding slice becomes a full departure-control module, including real seating rules.

- **Weight ****&**** Balance** — today a simulator behind a port; this phase brings a real adapter behind the same conformance suite.

- **Baggage** and **IROPS / disruption handling**.

- **Settlement ****&**** revenue-accounting integration.**

- **Cargo (CMS) integration.**

*Note: *ADR-0002 (flight-class identity) named the platform’s canonical cross-service identity but deliberately deferred implementing it. Its stated trigger is exactly this phase — the first Weight & Balance or IROPS work should implement it, not defer further.

## **6.3  Longer-term — Phase 4: Native Offer ****&**** Order + AI**

The platform roadmap's final phase, for context: full IATA ONE Order native fulfilment, dynamic/continuous pricing, AI-driven personalisation at scale, order-based interline agreements, and retirement of legacy PNR-bridge compatibility per carrier as each is ready. Not near-term — included here so the team has the full picture, not just the next sprint.

# **7. ****Handover: Repository, Access ****&**** Environment**

## **7.1  Repository access**

Repository: https://github.com/babakghf/pss-platform (private).

- Recommended sequence: add the incoming team as collaborators first, have them do a clean clone and a successful local build (§7.4), **then** transfer repository ownership. This avoids any access gap mid-transfer.

- The team should work from a fresh clone and the repository’s own documentation, rather than relying on any local uncommitted state on the outgoing owner’s machine.

## **7.2  Credentials ****&**** secrets — transfer out-of-band**

**Do not transfer secrets via email, chat, or this document.** Use a password manager or secrets vault your organisation already trusts. The following exist and need transfer:

- **.env** (repository root, not committed) — Razorpay sandbox API key, secret, and webhook secret.

- **Razorpay Dashboard access** (test mode) — needed to view/edit the webhook configuration described in §7.4.

- **ngrok account** — free tier, used to tunnel the local payments webhook for real end-to-end payment testing. A reserved subdomain is currently in use; confirm whether it transfers with the account or needs re-pointing in the Razorpay dashboard.

## **7.3  Where to start reading, in order**

- README.md — repository root.

- LATEST_STATUS.md — the living status file. Read this first in every session; it is kept current by design.

- docs/BUILD_PLAN_DEMO_PRODUCT.md — the canonical, current plan. Workstreams 3–5 are fully specified here.

- docs/adr/ — ADR-0001 (how decisions are recorded), ADR-0002 (flight-class identity), ADR-0003 (seller identity, Proposed — needs ratifying to start Workstream 3).

- DEMO_SCRIPT.md and docs/dr4/DR4_RESULTS.md — the rehearsed demo scenario and its last verified run.

- docs/contracts/ — every service’s OpenAPI + event-schema contract; the source of truth for any integration.

## **7.4  Local environment setup**

**Prerequisites: **Docker Desktop, JDK 21, and the included Gradle wrapper (no separate Gradle install needed).

**Build: **

cd platform && ./gradlew build

**Run the demo stack: **

docker compose -f docker-compose.demo.yml -f docker-compose.demo-full.yml up -d

./scripts/demo-reset-full.sh   # seeds demo data, runs a smoke booking

**Entry point once running: **http://localhost:8093/ — the branded landing page.

## **7.5  Environment gotchas worth knowing on day one**

- **Static UI assets are baked into service JARs at build time.** A source change to a page under a service’s static/ folder requires rebuilding that service’s JAR and recreating its container — restarting the container alone serves the old code.

- **The demo gateway’s nginx config is a bind-mounted file from the working tree.** Its content depends on which git branch is checked out when the container starts — switching branches with the stack already running can silently serve a stale config. Recreate the ibe-gateway container after any branch switch that touches gateway config.

- **Windows / Git Bash path handling: **commands with a leading-slash path (e.g. docker exec <container> cat /etc/...) can be silently rewritten to a Windows path by Git Bash. Wrap the command in sh -c "..." or prefix with MSYS_NO_PATHCONV=1 when this happens.

- **Real end-to-end payment testing needs three things simultaneously: **(1) ngrok http 8086 running and left open, (2) the Razorpay Dashboard webhook pointed at that tunnel’s URL and **Enabled** (confirm there is only one such webhook — a duplicate caused real confusion once), and (3) that webhook subscribed to at least payment.authorized, payment.captured, refund.processed, refund.failed. Without a live tunnel, checkout hangs on “Confirming your booking…” indefinitely with no error shown — check this first if that happens.

## **7.6  Continuing with AI-assisted development**

This project was built through paired sessions between a human operator and Claude Code (an agentic coding tool that works directly in the repository), with a separate Claude.ai project used for planning, prompt-writing, and review. If your team continues this pattern:

- docs/claude-project-sync/ is a folder maintained specifically to be uploaded into a Claude.ai project’s knowledge base, so AI-assisted planning stays grounded in the actual current repository state rather than a stale memory of it.

- The standing engineering rules this project follows — contract-first, the real-counterparty testing rule, “stop-and-flag” on any ambiguity rather than improvising, one PR per unit of work with an explicit human verification step before merge — are stated in docs/BUILD_PLAN_DEMO_PRODUCT.md and should be carried forward regardless of tooling.

- **The single most important habit from this project: **verify UI and integration changes by actually clicking through them in a browser against a live payment/booking, not by trusting a green CI status or an HTTP 200 alone. Several real defects in this codebase were invisible to every automated check and were only found this way.

## **7.7  What needs your attention first**

- Review and merge PR #95 and PR #96 (both green, both awaiting one live click-through — see §4.3).

- Read ADR-0003 and ratify or amend it — this unblocks Workstream 3.

- Proceed through Workstreams 3–5 and DR5 per docs/BUILD_PLAN_DEMO_PRODUCT.md.

# **8. ****Glossary**

| **Term** | **Meaning** |
| --- | --- |
| PSS | Passenger Service System — the airline software category this platform is. |
| PNR | Passenger Name Record / booking reference — the code a customer uses to look up a booking. |
| NDC | New Distribution Capability — IATA’s API standard for travel-agent distribution. |
| ADR | Architecture Decision Record — a written, dated record of a significant design decision and its rationale. |
| Fitness function | An automated check that runs in CI to enforce an architectural rule (e.g. “no service may call another service’s database directly”). |
| Thin slice | A deliberately minimal but real, end-to-end implementation of a feature — proves the architecture without building every edge case up front. |
| Real-counterparty rule | The project’s standing rule that a cross-service integration isn’t proven until a test exercises the real downstream service, not a mock/stub. |
| W0–W5 | The six workstreams of the Demo Product program — see §4.3. |
| DR4 / DR5 | “Demo Readiness” and “Demo Product” dry-run gates — full rehearsals of the platform before it is declared ready to show a client. |
| Compute-only | Describes Revenue Management’s current behaviour: it computes and displays a recommendation but never writes it back to Inventory. This is deliberate and stated on-screen, not a bug. |

